  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- Initial focus primarily on drug-related financial crimes\n- Limited international cooperation\n- Weak regulatory frameworks\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- 1989 Formation of Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\n3. Major Developments:\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory transaction reporting\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Stricter customer identification procedures\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n\n4. Technological Adaptations:\n- Regulations covering digital currencies\n- Enhanced cybersecurity requirements\n- Advanced transaction monitoring systems\n- Machine learning and AI-driven detection techniques\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Expanded scope beyond traditional financial institutions\n- Cryptocurrency and blockchain regulations\n- More aggressive penalties\n- Greater emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n\n6. Global Collaboration:\n- Harmonized international standards\n- Multilateral enforcement mechanisms\n- Coordinated investigative approaches\n\nThese legislative developments reflect ongoing efforts to address increasingly sophisticated money laundering techniques.",
